        <p>
          Oral nutrients may have variable absorption and first-pass metabolism, whereas IV
          administration delivers ingredients directly to the bloodstream for more predictable
          availability. Protocols are tailored to medical history and training load.
        </p>

        <h4>Pre-Event Protocol: Priming Muscles and Mind</h4>
        <p>
          <b>Timing:</b> 18–24 hours before the start. This window allows uptake without
          race-morning “heaviness.”
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Isotonic saline for baseline hydration</li>
          <li>Targeted amino acids (e.g., BCAAs) to limit muscle breakdown</li>
          <li>Vitamin C + N-acetyl-cysteine for antioxidant cover</li>
          <li>NAD⁺ (as clinically appropriate) for cellular energy and focus</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="note">
          Competitive athletes must always ensure compliance with sport regulations. Your nurse will
          align volume and documentation with applicable event rules and medical best practices.
        </p>

        <h4>Post-Event Recovery: Faster Rehydration and Less DOMS</h4>
        <p>
          The “golden hour” after finishing is ideal for rehydration and micronutrient support. A
          typical Recovery IV may include:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Magnesium for muscle relaxation</li>
          <li>Vitamin C and an antioxidant cofactor</li>
          <li>Balanced electrolyte fluid to restore volume</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          With blood volume restored promptly, protein repair begins sooner—often helping athletes
          return to training faster compared with fluids alone.
        </p>

        <h4>Personalising Your Bag with Lab &amp; DNA Tests</h4>
        <p>
          Everybody is different. A <b>Custom Blood Test</b> can identify iron, vitamin, or
          magnesium gaps that sap power. DNA insights can further guide choices (e.g., caffeine
          metabolism, muscle fibre tendencies). Your nurse reviews results, designs a plan, and
          tracks progress across the season.
        </p>

        <h4>Who Should Modify or Skip IV Therapy</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Kidney disease → avoid high magnesium; seek nephrology input</li>
          <li>Certain heart conditions or uncontrolled hypertension → cardiology review</li>
          <li>History of IV intolerance → start with small volume under supervision</li>
          <li>Pregnancy → basic fluids and standard vitamins only with OB clearance</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Always share your medical history so the team can tailor the protocol or offer an oral
          alternative if needed.
        </p>

